    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3970179841" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3970179841" />
    <a title="Stephanie Fleming" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46659053-stephanie-fleming"><img alt="Stephanie Fleming" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1441400980p2/46659053.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3970179841?book_show_action=true">Apr 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephanie Fleming" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephanie Fleming" href="/user/show/46659053-stephanie-fleming">Stephanie Fleming</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3970179841" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17280915621013348437">It&apos;s difficult to rate a book of short stories-some are very good, others were more middling. You can see why Saki is supposed to be one of the masters of the short story though- he has a really good turn of phrase!<br/><br/>The majority of the stories are centred around characters that would not be out of place in a Wodehouse book (which make sense, since both authors wrote in the Edwardian period). Saki&apos;s characters aren&apos;t nearly nice as Wooster and Jeeves though- they are a bit nastier and always happy</span>
  <span id="freeText17280915621013348437" style="display:none">It's difficult to rate a book of short stories-some are very good, others were more middling. You can see why Saki is supposed to be one of the masters of the short story though- he has a really good turn of phrase!<br /><br />The majority of the stories are centred around characters that would not be out of place in a Wodehouse book (which make sense, since both authors wrote in the Edwardian period). Saki's characters aren't nearly nice as Wooster and Jeeves though- they are a bit nastier and always happy to score points off someone. <br /><br />Clovis, the character that shows up most often throughout this set of stories is basically the embodiment of that saying about setting out to find trouble and making his own when he can't find it. Basically, if it was a modern character, he'd be a rich kid on Instagram and probably have his own prank channel (or possibly make-up/drama channel- his good traits are pretty much centred around him being pretty). He is generally only out for his own comfort and tends to send people up in a vaguely cruel way, unless you're of use to him (aka give him money). In the other hand, all of the characters these stories recognize this and aren't exactly kind and forgiving about it.<br /><br />In terms of writing, Saki is very good at hinting and describing, not outright telling you what is happening. Occasionally, this means you need to re-read to figure out what's happening (in the Easter Egg for example, I was very surprised by the twist there), but it works very well in short stories. He's also very big on calls out to classical Greek and Roman things, but that could also be the style of the times- I believe most English boys going to school then did Latin and all that. There are some period-typical racist references too.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17280915621013348437" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

