    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2083458452" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2083458452" />
    <a title="José" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10045353-jos"><img alt="José" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1375850942p2/10045353.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2083458452?book_show_action=true">Aug 13, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="José" class="user" itemprop="url" name="José" href="/user/show/10045353-jos">José</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2083458452" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1758459859437341376">Some writers belong to their time and place, others trascend any barriers imaginable, the short stories of Saki are well grounded in the former category but sometimes manage to reach the latter superbly. Mostly set in the world of Edwardian Era upper-class, he could be regarded as a missing link between Oscar Wilde and PG Wodehouse but his twisted sense of humor and creatively cruel imagination certainly makes him standout.<br/><br/>Hands down, my favorites were &quot;Sredni Vashtar&quot;, &quot;The Background&quot;, &quot;The Wa</span>
  <span id="freeText1758459859437341376" style="display:none">Some writers belong to their time and place, others trascend any barriers imaginable, the short stories of Saki are well grounded in the former category but sometimes manage to reach the latter superbly. Mostly set in the world of Edwardian Era upper-class, he could be regarded as a missing link between Oscar Wilde and PG Wodehouse but his twisted sense of humor and creatively cruel imagination certainly makes him standout.<br /><br />Hands down, my favorites were "Sredni Vashtar", "The Background", "The Way to the Dairy", "Mrs. Packletide's Tiger" and "The Hounds of Fate". Most of the weaker stories were the ones starring Clovis, the young British aristocrat who serve as a framing device or outright protagonist for most of the stories. I guess we were meant to find him charming in a cheeky scoundrel-type of way but he was just a mean, insufferable, self-entitled asshole, sorry.<br /><br />Probably the weakest stories were the ones satirizing then-contemporary politics, which badly suffer from outdated attitudes (He surely didn't like those Sufragettes) and how much politics have changed over a century. One of them, "Ministers of Grace", was the only story I couldn't finish. <br /><br />Overall, Saki is in his element when he's making larger-than-life caricatures filled with airs of authority and hipocrisy and setting particularly devious downfalls (more or often than not involving animals) or just letting an absurd situation grow and grow and you laugh at his colorful prose and snarky descriptions.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1758459859437341376" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


