<div id="review_3364534602" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3364534602" />
    <a title="Ashik" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/47904334-ashik"><img alt="Ashik" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1445057976p2/47904334.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3364534602?book_show_action=true">Jun 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ashik" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ashik" href="/user/show/47904334-ashik">Ashik</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781434651709" href="/book/show/2003481.The_Chronicles_of_Clovis">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3364534602" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10503028178413123401">There are a lot of good reviews here so I&apos;ll just add a few things:<br/><br/>1. Yes, these stories are rather morbid in tone (compared to Saki&apos;s other works. I&apos;d say Clovis character was built to have darker tendencies in his tales.) But there is also good old Saki-humour so no worries, you&apos;ll enjoy these.<br/>2. Yes, quite often there are some very grim, unforeseeable twists that might be unsettling for some. But Saki executes these twists with such skillful humor that these become rather enjoyable as well.<br/>3.</span>
  <span id="freeText10503028178413123401" style="display:none">There are a lot of good reviews here so I'll just add a few things:<br /><br />1. Yes, these stories are rather morbid in tone (compared to Saki's other works. I'd say Clovis character was built to have darker tendencies in his tales.) But there is also good old Saki-humour so no worries, you'll enjoy these.<br />2. Yes, quite often there are some very grim, unforeseeable twists that might be unsettling for some. But Saki executes these twists with such skillful humor that these become rather enjoyable as well.<br />3. I love how Saki chose the titles for his stories because they are meant to evoke a certain emotion or hint at a certain part of the story, which is not obvious at the beginning of the story. So I'd suggest that once you've read the story, go back and look at the title again because you'll have another laugh just from the clever titles.<br /><br />Some stories that I recommend-<br />For those who love dark humor: Esme, The unrest cure, The jesting of Arlington Stringham, Sredni Vashtar, The Easter egg, The music on the hill, the hounds of fate.<br /><br />Hilarious ones: Mrs. Packletide's tiger, The stampeding of lady Bastable, Hermann the Irascible, The chaplet, The peace offerings, The talking-out of Tarrington, The secret sin of Septimus Brope.<br /><br />Finally, if you liked this book, may I suggest Beasts and Super-beasts by Saki?</span>
  <a data-text-id="10503028178413123401" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


